9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 836, L.D. 1261, “An Act to Support At-
10 risk Families by Establishing the Community Navigator Pilot Program”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, to Establish the Community Navigator Pilot Program to Support At-risk
13 Families'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
15 'Sec. 1. Community Navigator Pilot Program. Resolved: That the Department
16 of Health and Human Services, referred to in this resolve as "the department," shall contract
17 with 2 child abuse and neglect prevention councils under the Maine Revised Statutes, Title
18 22, chapter 1057 to establish a 2-year pilot program, the Community Navigator Pilot
19 Program, referred to in this resolve as "the pilot program," for 2 community navigators. In
20 developing the contracts, the department shall determine which 2 child abuse and neglect
21 prevention councils are prepared to participate in the pilot program and ensure that one
22 child abuse and neglect prevention council is in a northern part of the State and the other is
23 in a southern part of the State. The department shall provide funding for each community
24 navigator in the amount of $90,000 per community navigator, per year, for both year one
25 and year 2 of the pilot program. The department shall award the contracts no later than
26 July 1, 2026, and the pilot program may not last longer than 2 years. The contracts must
27 include mechanisms for identifying families in need of services from community
28 navigators and for information sharing between community navigators and families.
29 Sec. 2. Services provided by community navigators to mandated reporters.
30 Resolved: That a community navigator under the pilot program shall engage in outreach
31 activities to provide education and guidance to mandated reporters, as set forth in the Maine
32 Revised Statutes, Title 22, section 4011-A, subsection 1. Education and guidance include
33 improving mandated reporters' knowledge of available services and resources for families,
34 educating mandated reporters on how to refer families to services where those families live
35 and providing guidelines for mandated reporters to work directly with families rather than
36 only reporting suspected child abuse or neglect.
